# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-sns
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-sns/amazon-simple-notification-service] Amazon SNS acts as a single message bus that can message to a variety of devices and platforms.
[src:aws-sns/amazon-simple-notification-service] A single code interface can address all of these equally, or message formats can be tailored to the particular needs of each platform.
[src:aws-sns/amazon-simple-notification-service] Amazon SNS can also deliver messages by SMS to 200+ countries.
[src:aws-sns/amazon-simple-notification-service] Amazon SNS uses the publish/subscribe model for delivery of messages.
[src:aws-sns/amazon-simple-notification-service] Recipients subscribe to one or more 'topics' within Amazon SNS.
[src:aws-sns/amazon-simple-notification-service] This may be hidden from the user as an internal part of a mobile app.
[src:aws-sns/amazon-simple-notification-service] Receipt of a message may also be hidden from the user: this service is largely aimed at the internal processing of specific apps rather than as a generic email substitute.
[src:aws-sns/amazon-simple-notification-service] A game might receive bonus-level announcements or unlock keys for in-game purchases by this route.
[src:aws-sns/amazon-simple-notification-service] A ticket booking app could use it for confirmation vouchers, boarding passes or notifications of a delay to a flight.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] An **enterprise service bus** (**ESB**) implements a communication system between mutually interacting software applications in a service-oriented architecture (SOA).
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] It represents a software architecture for distributed computing, and is a special variant of the more general client-server model, wherein any application may behave as server or client.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] ESB promotes agility and flexibility with regard to high-level protocol communication between applications.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] Its primary use is in enterprise application integration (EAI) of heterogeneous and complex service landscapes.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] The concept of the enterprise service bus is analogous to the bus concept found in computer hardware architecture combined with the modular and concurrent design of high-performance computer operating systems.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] ESB is also a common implementation pattern for service-oriented architecture, including the intrinsically adopted network design of the World Wide Web.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] No global standards exist for enterprise service bus concepts or implementations.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] Most providers of message-oriented middleware have adopted the enterprise service bus concept as *de facto* standard for a service-oriented architecture.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] The implementations of ESB use event-driven and standards-based message-oriented middleware in combination with message queues as technology frameworks.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] However, some software manufacturers relabel existing middleware and communication solutions as ESB without adopting the crucial aspect of a bus concept.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] An ESB applies the design concept of modern operating systems to independent services running within networks of disparate and independent computers.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] Like concurrent operating systems, an ESB provides commodity services in addition to adoption, translation and routing of client requests to appropriate answering services.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] The first published usage of the term "enterprise service bus" is attributed to Roy W.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] Schulte from the Gartner Group 2002 and the book *The Enterprise Service Bus* by David Chappell.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] Roma was first sold in 1998 making it the first commercial ESB in the market, but that Sonic's product from 2002 was also one of the early ESBs on the market.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] The ESB is implemented in software that operates between the business applications, and enables communication among them.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] Ideally, the ESB should be able to replace all direct contact with the applications on the bus, so that all communication takes place via the ESB.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] To achieve this objective, the ESB must encapsulate the functionality offered by its component applications in a meaningful way.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] This typically occurs through the use of an enterprise message model.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] The message model defines a standard set of messages that the ESB transmits and receives.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] When the ESB receives a message, it routes the message to the appropriate application.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] Often, because that application evolved without the same message model, the ESB has to transform the message into a format that the application can interpret.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] A software adapter fulfills the task of effecting these transformations, analogously to a physical adapter.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] ESBs rely on accurately constructing the enterprise message model and properly designing the functionality offered by applications.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] If the message model does not completely encapsulate the application functionality, then other applications that desire that functionality may have to bypass the bus, and invoke the mismatched applications directly.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] Doing so violates the principles of the ESB model, and negates many of the advantages of using this architecture.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] The beauty of the ESB lies in its platform-agnostic nature and the ability to integrate with anything at any condition.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] It is important that Application Lifecycle Management vendors truly apply all the ESB capabilities in their integration products while adopting SOA.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] Therefore, the challenges and opportunities for EAI vendors are to provide an integration solution that is low-cost, easily configurable, intuitive, user-friendly, and open to any tools customers choose.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] ¹ *Some do not regard process choreography as an ESB function.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] These solutions often focus on low-level ESB functions, such as connectivity, routing and transformation, and require coding or scripting to implement orchestration.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] If the message broker, the ESB software, translates a message from one format to another, then as with any translation, there is the issue of semantics of the message.
[src:aws-sns/enterprise-service-bus] For the known corner cases the number of tests that cover all corner cases increases exponentially with every application that is connected to the ESB, because every ESB-connected application must be tested against every other application that is connected to the ESB.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] In information technology, a **notification system** is a combination of software and hardware that delivers a message to a set of recipients.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] It commonly displays activity related to an account.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] These systems are an important aspect of modern web applications.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] The widespread adoption of notification systems was a major technological development of the 20th century.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] A notification is a combination of software, hardware, and psychology that provides a means of delivering a message to a group of recipients.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] Notifications show activity that relates to an event, account, or person.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] A push notification is a message that appears on a mobile device such as a text, sports score, limited-time deal, or an e-mail announcing when a computer network will be down for scheduled maintenance.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] Notifications are sent from app publishers at any time in an effort to get users to open up their app or website.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] Notifications appear on a user's lock screen and also at the top of their phone screen when the phone is unlocked and in use.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] In most newer devices, notifications appearing on the lock screen can be turned off, typically via an option in the device's settings.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] Push notifications can be valuable and convenient for both the app user and the developer due to the immediacy and display location of notifications.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] Notifications also pair with sounds to reach multiple senses of a user and reach maximum attention.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] For app publishers, push notifications are a way for them to speak directly to the user without being caught by spam filters or being pushed to the side by the flood of emails within an inbox.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] Because of this, these push click-through rates can be higher than email.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] They invite users to open an app or spend time and money in a certain way by the app publisher, even when the app isn't open.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] This means that for developers, publishers, and businesses, notifications are the most effective way to take attention and ultimately make money.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] Notifications use a concept known as variable rewards, which is a technique that slot machines use to engage gamblers.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] Similarly, variable reward systems keep users compulsively checking their phones due to the possibility of social approval awaiting them.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] Social psychologist Jonathan Haidt at NYU Stern School of Business points to concerns of mental health directly relating to social media and the notification system.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] He points to the increase in depression and suicide rates among teens and young adults since the early 2000s, and Haidt states that this trend started the year social media was made available on cell phones.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] This is always used to drive larger profits, whether that means that companies use notifications to simply promote their newest product, or if they subtly try to get you back onto the app in order to take more of your time.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] There is overwhelming evidence that notifications are associated with decreased productivity, poorer concentration, and increased distraction at work, school, and home.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] "Ping fatigue" is the mental exhaustion created by endless digital notifications (pings).
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] The notifications arise from emails, instant messaging, package arrivals, workflow updates, and other digital tools and may disruptive to employee flow, negatively impacting productivity.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] The ever-present notifications lend to a sense of an infinite workday and lead to occupational burnout.
[src:aws-sns/notification-system] The number of ways a person can interact with technology has steadily increased.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] In push technology, clients can express their preferences for certain types of information or data, typically through a process known as the publish–subscribe model.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] In this model, a client "subscribes" to specific information channels hosted by a server.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] When new content becomes available on these channels, the server automatically sends, or "pushes," this information to the subscribed client.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Under certain conditions, such as restrictive security policies that block incoming HTTP requests, push technology is sometimes simulated using a technique called polling.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] In these cases, the client periodically checks with the server to see if new information is available, rather than receiving automatic updates.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Synchronous conferencing and instant messaging are examples of push services.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Chat messages and sometimes files are pushed to the user as soon as they are received by the messaging service.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Both decentralized peer-to-peer programs (such as WASTE) and centralized programs (such as IRC or XMPP) allow pushing files, which means the sender initiates the data transfer rather than the recipient.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Email may also be a push system: SMTP is a push protocol (see Push e-mail).
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] However, the last step—from mail server to desktop computer—typically uses a pull protocol like POP3 or IMAP.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Modern e-mail clients make this step seem instantaneous by repeatedly polling the mail server, frequently checking it for new mail.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The IMAP protocol includes the IDLE command, which allows the server to tell the client when new messages arrive.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The original BlackBerry was the first popular example of push-email in a wireless context.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Another example is the PointCast Network, which was widely covered in the 1990s.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] It delivered news and stock market data as a screensaver.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Both Netscape and Microsoft integrated push technology through the Channel Definition Format (CDF) into their software at the height of the browser wars, but it was never very popular.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Other uses of push-enabled web applications include software updates distribution ("push updates"), market data distribution (stock tickers), online chat/messaging systems (webchat), auctions, online betting and gaming, sport results, monitoring consoles, and sensor network monitoring.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The Web push proposal of the Internet Engineering Task Force is a simple protocol using HTTP version 2 to deliver real-time events, such as incoming calls or messages, which can be delivered (or "pushed") in a timely fashion.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The protocol consolidates all real-time events into a single session which ensures more efficient use of network and radio resources.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] A single service consolidates all events, distributing those events to applications as they arrive.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] This requires just one session, avoiding duplicated overhead costs.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Web Notifications are part of the W3C standard and define an API for end-user notifications.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] A notification allows alerting the user of an event, such as the delivery of an email, outside the context of a web page.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] As part of this standard, Push API is fully implemented in Chrome, Firefox, and Edge, and partially implemented in Safari as of February 2023.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] HTTP server push (also known as HTTP streaming) is a mechanism for sending unsolicited (asynchronous) data from a web server to a web browser.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] HTTP server push can be achieved through any of several mechanisms.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] As a part of HTML5 the Web Socket API allows a web server and client to communicate over a full-duplex TCP connection.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Generally, the web server does not terminate a connection after response data has been served to a client.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The web server leaves the connection open so that if an event occurs (for example, a change in internal data which needs to be reported to one or multiple clients), it can be sent out immediately; otherwise, the event would have to be queued until the client's next request is received.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Most web servers offer this functionality via CGI (e.g., Non-Parsed Headers scripts on Apache HTTP Server).
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The underlying mechanism for this approach is chunked transfer encoding.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Another mechanism is related to a special MIME type called `multipart/x-mixed-replace`, which was introduced by Netscape in 1995.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Web browsers interpret this as a document that changes whenever the server pushes a new version to the client.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] It is still supported by Firefox, Opera, and Safari today, but it is ignored by Internet Explorer and is only partially supported by Chrome.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] It can be applied to HTML documents, and also for streaming images in webcam applications.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The WHATWG Web Applications 1.0 proposal includes a mechanism to push content to the client.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] On September 1, 2006, the Opera web browser implemented this new experimental system in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] In this technique, the server takes advantage of persistent HTTP connections, leaving the response perpetually "open" (i.e., the server never terminates the response), effectively fooling the browser to remain in "loading" mode after the initial page load could be considered complete.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The server then periodically sends snippets of JavaScript to update the content of the page, thereby achieving push capability.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] By using this technique, the client doesn't need Java applets or other plug-ins in order to keep an open connection to the server; the client is automatically notified about new events, pushed by the server.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] One serious drawback to this method, however, is the lack of control the server has over the browser timing out; a page refresh is always necessary if a timeout occurs on the browser end.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Long polling is itself not a true push; long polling is a variation of the traditional polling technique, but it allows emulating a push mechanism under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP requests.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] With long polling, the client requests to get more information from the server exactly as in normal polling, but with the expectation that the server may not respond immediately.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] If the server has no new information for the client when the poll is received, then instead of sending an empty response, the server holds the request open and waits for response information to become available.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Once it does have new information, the server immediately sends an HTTP response to the client, completing the open HTTP request.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Upon receipt of the server response, the client often immediately issues another server request.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] In this way the usual response latency (the time between when the information first becomes available and the next client request) otherwise associated with polling clients is eliminated.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] This technique, used by chat applications, makes use of the XML Socket object in a single-pixel Adobe Flash movie.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Under the control of JavaScript, the client establishes a TCP connection to a unidirectional relay on the server.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The relay server does not read anything from this socket; instead, it immediately sends the client a unique identifier.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Next, the client makes an HTTP request to the web server, including this identifier with it.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The web application can then push messages addressed to the client to a local interface of the relay server, which relays them over the Flash socket.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The advantage of this approach is that it appreciates the natural read-write asymmetry that is typical of many web applications, including chat, and as a consequence it offers high efficiency.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Since it does not accept data on outgoing sockets, the relay server does not need to poll outgoing TCP connections *at all*, making it possible to hold open tens of thousands of concurrent connections.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] In this model, the limit to scale is the TCP stack of the underlying server operating system.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] In services such as cloud computing, to increase reliability and availability of data, it is usually pushed (replicated) to several machines.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] For example, the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) makes 2 extra copies of any object stored.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] RGDD focuses on efficiently casting an object from one location to many while saving bandwidth by sending minimal number of copies (only one in the best case) of the object over any link across the network.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] For example, Datacast is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside data centers that relies on regular and structured topologies and DCCast is a similar approach for delivery across data centers.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] A push notification is a message that is "pushed" from a back-end server or application to a user interface, e.g. mobile applications or desktop applications.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Apple introduced push notifications for iPhone in 2009, and in 2010 Google released "Google Cloud to Device Messaging" (superseded by Google Cloud Messaging and then by Firebase Cloud Messaging).
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Push notifications are mainly divided into two approaches, local notifications and remote notifications.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] For local notifications, the application schedules the notification with the local device's OS.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The application sets a timer in the application itself, provided it is able to continuously run in the background.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] When the event's scheduled time is reached, or the event's programmed condition is met, the message is displayed in the application's user interface.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Remote notifications are handled by a remote server.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Under this scenario, the client application needs to be registered on the server with a unique key (e.g., a UUID or Apple *Device Token*).
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The server then transmits the message against the unique key to deliver it to the client via an agreed client/server protocol such as HTTP or XMPP.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] When the push notification arrives at the client, it can cause the display of short notifications or messages, set badges on application icons, blink or continuously light up the notification LED, or play alert sounds to attract user's attention.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Push notifications are usually used by applications to bring information to users' attention.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] Real-time push notifications may raise privacy issues since they can be used to bind virtual identities of social network pseudonyms to the real identities of the smartphone owners.
[src:aws-sns/push-technology] The use of unnecessary push notifications for promotional purposes has been criticized as an example of attention theft.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Developed as part of the GSM standards, and based on the SS7 signalling protocol, SMS rolled out on digital cellular networks starting in 1993 and was originally intended for customers to receive alerts from their carrier/operator.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The service allows users to send and receive text messages of up to 160 characters, originally to and from GSM phones and later also CDMA and Digital AMPS; it has since been defined and supported on newer networks, including present-day 5G ones.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Using SMS gateways, messages can be transmitted over the Internet through an SMSC, allowing communication to computers, fixed landlines, and satellite.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] MMS was later introduced as an upgrade to SMS with "picture messaging" capabilities.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In addition to recreational texting between people, SMS is also used for mobile marketing (a type of direct marketing), two-factor authentication logging-in, televoting, mobile banking (see SMS banking), and for other commercial content.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The SMS standard has been hugely popular worldwide as a method of text communication: by the end of 2010, it was the most widely used data application with an estimated 3.5 billion active users, or about 80% of all mobile phone subscribers.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] More recently, SMS has become increasingly challenged by newer proprietary instant messaging services; Rich Communication Services (RCS) has been designated as the potential open standard successor to SMS.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS technology originated from radio telegraphy in radio memo pagers that used standardized phone protocols.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] These were defined in 1986 as part of the Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM) series of standards.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The first SMS message was sent on 3 December 1992, when Neil Papworth, a test engineer for Sema Group, sent "Merry Christmas" to the Orbitel 901 phone of colleague Richard Jarvis.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Adding text messaging functionality to mobile devices began in the early 1980s.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The SMS concept was developed in the Franco-German GSM cooperation in 1984 by Friedhelm Hillebrand and Bernard Ghillebaert.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The GSM is optimized for telephony, since this was identified as its main application.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The key idea for SMS was to use this telephone-optimized system, and to transport messages on the signalling paths needed to control the telephone traffic during periods when no signalling traffic existed.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In this way, unused resources in the system could be used to transport messages at minimal cost.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] However, it was necessary to limit the length of the messages to 128 bytes (later improved to 160 seven-bit characters) so that the messages could fit into the existing signalling formats.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Based on his personal observations and on analysis of the typical lengths of postcard and Telex messages, Hillebrand argued that 160 characters was sufficient for most brief communications.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS could be implemented in every mobile station by updating its software.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Hence, a large base of SMS-capable terminals and networks existed when people began to use SMS.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] A new network element required was a specialized short message service centre, and enhancements were required to the radio capacity and network transport infrastructure to accommodate growing SMS traffic.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The technical development of SMS was a multinational collaboration supporting the framework of standards bodies.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Through these organizations the technology was made freely available to the whole world.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The first proposal which initiated the development of SMS was made by a contribution of Germany and France in the GSM group meeting in February 1985 in Oslo.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] This proposal was further elaborated in GSM subgroup WP1 Services (Chairman Martine Alvernhe, France Telecom) based on a contribution from Germany.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] There were also initial discussions in the subgroup WP3 network aspects chaired by Jan Audestad (Telenor).
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The result was approved by the main GSM group in a June 1985 document which was distributed to industry.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The input documents on SMS had been prepared by Friedhelm Hillebrand of Deutsche Telekom, with contributions from Bernard Ghillebaert of France Télécom.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The definition that Friedhelm Hillebrand and Bernard Ghillebaert brought into GSM called for the provision of a message transmission service of alphanumeric messages to mobile users "with acknowledgement capabilities".
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The last three words transformed SMS into something much more useful than the electronic paging services used at the time that some in GSM might have had in mind.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS was considered in the main GSM group as a possible service for the new digital cellular system.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In GSM document "*Services and Facilities to be provided in the GSM System,*" both mobile-originated and mobile-terminated short messages appear on the table of GSM teleservices.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Short message mobile-originated (SMS-MO)/ Point-to-Point: the ability of a network to transmit a Short Message sent by a mobile phone.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The message can be sent to a phone or to a software application.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] WP4 created a Drafting Group Message Handling (DGMH), which was responsible for the specification of SMS.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Finn Trosby of Telenor chaired the draft group through its first three years, in which the design of SMS was established.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] DGMH had five to eight participants, and Finn Trosby mentions as major contributors Kevin Holley, Eija Altonen, Didier Luizard and Alan Cox.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The first action plan mentions for the first time the Technical Specification 03.40 "Technical Realisation of the Short Message Service".
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The first and very rudimentary draft of the technical specification was completed in November 1987.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] However, drafts useful for the manufacturers followed at a later stage in the period.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] A comprehensive description of the work in this period is given in.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The first SMS message was sent over the Vodafone GSM network in the United Kingdom on 3 December 1992, from Neil Papworth of Sema Group (now Mavenir Systems) using a personal computer to Richard Jarvis of Vodafone using an Orbitel 901 handset.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The first commercial deployment of a short message service center (SMSC) was by Aldiscon part of Logica (now part of CGI) with Telia (now TeliaSonera) in Sweden in 1993, followed by Fleet Call (now Nextel) in the US, Telenor in Norway and BT Cellnet (now O2 UK).
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The first commercially sold SMS service was offered to consumers, as a person-to-person text messaging service by Radiolinja (now part of Elisa) in Finland in 1993.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Most early GSM mobile phone handsets did not support the ability to send SMS text messages, and Nokia was the only handset manufacturer whose total GSM phone line in 1993 supported user-sending of SMS text messages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] According to Matti Makkonen, an engineer at Nokia at the time, the Nokia 2010, which was released in January 1994, was the first mobile phone to support composing SMSes easily.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Initial growth was slow, with customers in 1995 sending on average only 0.4 messages per GSM customer per month.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Initially, networks in the UK only allowed customers to send messages to other users on the same network, limiting the usefulness of the service.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Over time, this issue was eliminated by switch billing instead of billing at the SMSC and by new features within SMSCs to allow blocking of foreign mobile users sending messages through it.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] By the end of 2000, the average number of messages reached 35 per user per month, and on Christmas Day 2006, over 205 million messages were sent in the UK alone.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS had become a social phenomenon in Finland among teens and youngsters by 1999.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS traffic across Europe reached 4 billion messages as of January 2000.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS became extremely popular in the Philippines by 2001 and the country was dubbed the "texting capital of the world", partly helped by large numbers of free text messages offered by the mobile operators in monthly subscriptions.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS adoption was limited to parts of Europe and Asia during these earlier years, with U.S. adoption being low partly due to incompatible networks and cheap voice calls relative to other countries.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS has become a large commercial industry, earning $114.6 billion globally in 2010.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In the year 2002, 366 billion SMS text messages were sent globally, a number that rose to 6.1 trillion in 2010.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In 2015, the actual cost of sending an SMS in Australia was found to be $0.00016 per SMS.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The global SMS messaging business was estimated to be worth over US$240 billion in 2013, accounting for almost half of all revenue generated by mobile messaging.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The popularity of SMS also led to the spontaneous creation of the so-called 'SMS language' phenomenon, where words are shortened in order to deal with the 160 character limit of SMS messages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Usage of SMS for mobile data services became increasingly prominent in the early 2000s due to its ubiquity, reliability, and cold reception of the newer WAP standard.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In the early and mid 2000s, Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS) was developed as an improved version of SMS that supports sending of pictures and video.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS has been increasingly challenged by Internet Protocol-based messaging services with additional features for modern mobile devices, such as Facebook Messenger, WhatsApp, Telegram, or WeChat.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] These services run independently from mobile network operators and typically don't provide cross-platform messaging capabilities like SMS or email does.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] For example, between 2010 and 2022, SMS telecom revenue in India dropped 94 percent, while "revenue share per user from data usage...grew over 10 times.", although in some regions such as North America SMS continues to be used by over 80 percent of the population as of 2023.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In order to create a modern successor to SMS that isn't run by a single company and is fully interoperable between devices, industry figures have created the RCS 'Universal Profile' initiative.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] It was supported by Apple when iOS 18 came out in 2024, which will mean that virtually all new mobile phones (iOS and Android platforms) will have RCS texting capabilities, though this may also depend on if the network operator supports it.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS may be used to provide premium rate services to subscribers of a network.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Today, they are also used to pay smaller payments online—for example, for file-sharing services, in mobile application stores, or VIP section entrance.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Outside the online world, one can buy a bus ticket or beverages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Additionally, an intermediary service can facilitate a text-to-voice conversion to be sent to landlines.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In 2014, Caktus Group developed the world's first SMS-based voter registration system in Libya.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] As of February 2015 more than 1.5 million people have registered using that system, providing Libyan voters with unprecedented access to the democratic process.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] A Flash SMS is a type of SMS that appears directly on the main screen without user interaction and is not automatically stored in the inbox.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] It can be useful in emergencies, such as a fire alarm or cases of confidentiality, as in delivering one-time passwords.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In 2010, almost half a million silent SMS messages were sent by the German federal police, customs and the federal domestic intelligence service Verfassungsschutz.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] These silent messages, also known as silent TMS, stealth SMS, stealth ping or Short Message Type 0, are used to locate a person and thus to create a complete movement profile.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] They do not show up on a display, nor trigger any acoustical signal when received.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Their primary purpose was to deliver special services of the network operator to any cell phone.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In March 2001, Dutch police in Amsterdam attempted to fight increasing cell phone theft by sending an SMS every three minutes to a phone that has been reported stolen, with the message "This handset was nicked, buying or selling is a crime.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The *Short Message Service—Point to Point (SMS-PP)*—was originally defined in GSM recommendation 03.40, which is now maintained in 3GPP as TS 23.040.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] GSM 03.41 (now 3GPP TS 23.041) defines the *Short Message Service—Cell Broadcast (SMS-CB)*, which allows messages (advertising, public information, etc.) to be broadcast to all mobile users in a specified geographical area.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Cell broadcast is the technology behind Wireless Emergency Alerts in the US which is used for public safety messages and AMBER alerts, and similar public safety messages in other countries.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] These messages are similar to SMS messages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Messages are sent to a short message service center (SMSC), which provides a "store and forward" mechanism.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] It attempts to send messages to the SMSC's recipients.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] If a recipient is not reachable, the SMSC queues the message for later retry.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Some SMSCs also provide a "forward and forget" option where transmission is tried only once.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Both mobile terminated (MT, for messages sent *to* a mobile handset) and mobile originating (MO, for those sent *from* the mobile handset) operations are supported.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Message delivery is "best effort", so there are no guarantees that a message will actually be delivered to its recipient, but delay or complete loss of a message is uncommon, typically affecting less than 5 percent of messages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Some providers allow users to request delivery reports, either via the SMS settings of most modern phones, or by prefixing each message with *0#.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Transmission of short messages between the SMSC and the handset is done whenever using the Mobile Application Part (MAP) of the SS7 protocol.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Messages are sent with the MAP MO- and MT-ForwardSM operations, whose payload length is limited by the constraints of the signaling protocol to precisely 140 bytes (140 bytes × 8 bits / byte = 1120 bits).
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Short messages can be encoded using a variety of alphabets: the default GSM 7-bit alphabet, the 8-bit data alphabet, and the 16-bit UCS-2 or UTF-16 alphabets.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Depending on which alphabet the subscriber has configured in the handset, this leads to the maximum individual short message sizes of 160 7-bit characters, 140 8-bit characters, or 70 16-bit characters.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] GSM 7-bit alphabet support is mandatory for GSM handsets and network elements.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Larger content (concatenated SMS, multipart or segmented SMS, or "long SMS") can be sent using multiple messages, in which case each message will start with a User Data Header (UDH) containing segmentation information.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Since UDH is part of the payload, the number of available characters per segment is lower: 153 for 7-bit encoding, 134 for 8-bit encoding and 67 for 16-bit encoding.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The receiving handset is then responsible for reassembling the message and presenting it to the user as one long message.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] While the standard theoretically permits up to 255 segments, 10 segments is the practical maximum with some carriers, and long messages are often billed as equivalent to multiple SMS messages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In some cases 127 segments are supported.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] On some carriers non-subscribers can send messages to a subscriber's phone using an Email-to-SMS gateway.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Additionally, many carriers, including AT&T Mobility, T-Mobile USA, Sprint, and Verizon Wireless, offer the ability to do this through their respective websites.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] For example, an AT&T subscriber whose phone number was 555-555-5555 would receive emails addressed to 5555555555@txt.att.net as text messages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Subscribers can easily reply to these SMS messages, and the SMS reply is sent back to the original email address.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Sending email to SMS is free for the sender, but the recipient is subject to the standard delivery charges.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Only the first 160 characters of an email message can be delivered to a phone, and only 160 characters can be sent from a phone.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] However, longer messages may be broken up into multiple texts, depending upon the telephone service provider.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Text-enabled fixed-line handsets are required to receive messages in text format.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] However, messages can be delivered to non enabled phones using text-to-speech conversion.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Short messages can send binary content such as ringtones or logos, as well as Over-the-air programming (OTA) or configuration data.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Such uses are a vendor-specific extension of the GSM specification and there are multiple competing standards, although Nokia's Smart Messaging is common.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] GPRS is offered by smaller telco players as a route of sending SMS text to reduce the cost of SMS texting internationally.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The Mobile Application Part (MAP) of the SS7 protocol included support for the transport of Short Messages through the Core Network from its inception.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] MAP Phase 2 expanded support for SMS by introducing a separate operation code for Mobile Terminated Short Message transport.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Many mobile and satellite transceiver units support the sending and receiving of SMS using an extended version of the Hayes command set.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The extensions were standardised as part of the GSM Standards and extended as part of the 3GPP standards process.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The connection between the terminal equipment and the transceiver can be realized with a serial cable (e.g., USB), a Bluetooth link, an infrared link, etc.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Common AT commands include AT+CMGS (send message), AT+CMSS (send message from storage), AT+CMGL (list messages) and AT+CMGR (read message).
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] However, not all modern devices support receiving of messages if the message storage (for instance the device's internal memory) is not accessible using AT commands.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] An alternative to inbound SMS is based on long numbers (international number format, such as "+44 762 480 5000"), which can be used in place of short codes for SMS reception in several applications, such as TV voting, product promotions and campaigns.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Long numbers work internationally, allow businesses to use their own numbers, rather than short codes, which are usually shared across many brands.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Additionally, long numbers are nonpremium inbound numbers.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Threaded SMS is a visual styling orientation of SMS message history that arranges messages to and from a contact in chronological order on a single screen.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Visually, this style of representation provides a back-and-forth chat-like history for each individual contact.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Hierarchical-threading at the conversation-level (as typical in blogs and online messaging boards) is not widely supported by SMS messaging clients.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Session-tracking is used to extend the functionality of many Instant Messenger (IM) applications such that they are able to communicate over two-way dialogues with the much larger SMS user-base.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] While SMS reached its popularity as a person-to-person messaging, another type of SMS became popular by 2017: application-to-person (A2P) messaging.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] A2P is a type of SMS sent from a subscriber to an application or sent from an application to a subscriber.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] It is commonly used by businesses, such as banks, e-gaming, logistic companies, e-commerce, to send SMS messages from their systems to their customers.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In the US, carriers have traditionally preferred that A2P messages be sent using a short code rather than a standard long code.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In 2021, US carriers introduced a new service called A2P 10DLC, supporting the used of 10-digit long codes for A2P messages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In the United Kingdom A2P messages can be sent with a dynamic 11 character sender ID; however, short codes are used for OPTOUT commands.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] While early Iridium handsets only support incoming SMS, later models can also send messages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The price per message varies for different networks.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Unlike some mobile phone networks, there is no extra charge for sending international SMS or to send one to a different satellite phone network.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS can sometimes be sent from areas where the signal is too poor to make a voice call.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Satellite phone networks usually have web-based or email-based SMS portals where one can send free SMS to phones on that particular network.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Unlike dedicated texting systems like the Simple Network Paging Protocol and Motorola's ReFLEX protocol, SMS message delivery is not guaranteed, and many implementations provide no mechanism through which a sender can determine whether an SMS message has been delivered in a timely manner.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS messages are generally treated as lower-priority traffic than voice, and various studies have shown that around 1% to 5% of messages are lost entirely, even during normal operation conditions, and others may not be delivered until long after their relevance has passed.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The use of SMS as an emergency notification service in particular has been questioned.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The Global Service for Mobile communications (GSM), with the greatest worldwide number of users, succumbs to several security vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In the GSM, only the airway traffic between the Mobile Station (MS) and the Base Transceiver Station (BTS) is optionally encrypted with a weak and broken stream cipher (A5/1 or A5/2).
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The authentication is unilateral and also vulnerable.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] There are also many other security vulnerabilities and shortcomings.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Such vulnerabilities are inherent to SMS as one of the superior and well-tried services with a global availability in the GSM networks.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] SMS messaging has some extra security vulnerabilities due to its store-and-forward feature, and the problem of fake SMS that can be conducted via the Internet.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] When a user is roaming, SMS content passes through different networks, perhaps including the Internet, and is exposed to various vulnerabilities and attacks.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Another concern arises when an adversary gets access to a phone and reads the previous unprotected messages.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In October 2005, researchers from the Pennsylvania State University published an analysis of vulnerabilities in SMS-capable cellular networks.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The researchers speculated that attackers might exploit the open functionality of these networks to disrupt them or cause them to fail, possibly on a nationwide scale.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The GSM industry has identified a number of potential fraud attacks on mobile operators that can be delivered via abuse of SMS messaging services.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] One threat is SMS spoofing, which occurs when a fraudster manipulates address information in order to impersonate a user that has roamed onto a foreign network and is submitting messages to the home network.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] Frequently, these messages are addressed to destinations outside the home network—with the home SMSC essentially being "hijacked" to send messages into other networks.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] The only sure way of detecting and blocking spoofed messages is to screen incoming mobile-originated messages to verify that the sender is a valid subscriber and that the message is coming from a valid and correct location.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] This can be implemented by adding an intelligent routing function to the network that can query originating subscriber details from the home location register (HLR) before the message is submitted for delivery.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] This kind of intelligent routing function is beyond the capabilities of legacy messaging infrastructure.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] In an effort to limit telemarketers who had taken to bombarding users with hordes of unsolicited messages, India introduced new regulations in September 2011, including a cap of 3,000 SMS messages per subscriber per month, or an average of 100 per subscriber per day.
[src:aws-sns/short-message-service] However, it was ruled unconstitutional by the Delhi high court, but there are some limitations.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] In web development, a **webhook** is a method of augmenting or altering the behavior of a web page or web application with custom callbacks.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] These callbacks may be maintained, modified, and managed by third-party users who need not be affiliated with the originating website or application.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] In 2007, Jeff Lindsay coined the term *webhook* from the computer programming term *hook*.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] Webhooks are "user-defined HTTP callbacks".
[src:aws-sns/webhook] They are usually triggered by some event, such as pushing code to a repository, a purchase, a comment being posted to a blog and many more use cases.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] When that event occurs, the source site makes an HTTP request to the URL configured for the webhook.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] Users can configure them to cause events on one site to invoke behavior on another.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] Common uses are to trigger builds with continuous integration systems or to notify bug tracking systems.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] Because webhooks use HTTP, they can be integrated into web services without adding new infrastructure.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] When the client (the originating website or application) makes a webhook call to the third-party user's server, the incoming POST request should be authenticated to avoid a spoofing attack and its timestamp verified to avoid a replay attack.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] The sender may choose to keep a constant list of IP addresses from which requests will be sent.
[src:aws-sns/webhook] This is not a sufficient security measure on its own, but it is useful for when the receiving endpoint is behind a firewall or NAT.
